definition.value: A realizable entity  the manifestation of which brings about some result or end that is not essential to a continuant  in virtue of the kind of thing that it is but that can be served or participated in by that kind of continuant  in some kinds of natural, social or institutional contexts.
An independent continuant that is spatially extended whose identity is independent of that of other entities and can be maintained through time.
A gall trait in which the gall parenchyma is juicy, as in the tissue of some fruits (for example grapes, starfruit).
An anatomical space that is an opening through which a gall-inhabiting organism has emerged.
A plant anatomical space that is located inside a gall.
A gall structure that is attractive to another organism, usually ants, and which facilitates dispersal of the gall
A gall structure wherein the gall inducer and/or its associates resides and which includes a portion of nutritive tissue.
A larval chamber that is detached from the plant but enclosed in a cavity.
A quality that inheres in the portion of a gall that is internal.
A gall trait in which a larval chamber is suspended medially in the parenchyma by radiating plant fibers inside a largely hollow chamber.
An internal gall trait in which a gall has a single larval chamber for the gall-inducing insect.
An internal gall trait in which the tissue is reminiscent of pith, the relatively soft tissue at the center of a shoot axis.
An internal gall trait in which more than one larval chamber is present for the inducer species.
An internal gall trait in which the gall lacks macroscopic anatomical space(s) that is/are not the larval chamber.
A gall quality in which a gall has nectaries present.
A shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's having a shape resembling a canelé, a French pastry.
A shape inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer resembling a cup, with a depression and rim-like edge apically.
A shape trait in which a gall has radiating, spine-like processes that resemble the spines of a sea urchin (cf. Cidaridae).
A shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer being shaped like a funnel, abruptly widening from a narrow cylindrical part, to a wider distal part.
A shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being shaped like a lentil, with convex upper and lower surfaces.
A shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's appearing semicircular in cross-section, flat on one side, rounded on the other.
A spatial pattern (or gall arrangement) in which adjacent objects (galls) are positioned in such a way that each gall cannot readily be distinguished as an individual.

A color pattern inhering in a bearer by virtue of bearer's being marked with one hue or degree of saturation near one pole and a different hue or degree of saturation at the opposite pole and a color gradient between the two poles.
A texture quality in which the surface is marked by alternating parallel ridges and grooves.
A texture quality in which the surface is marked by a network of cracks, as in craquelure.
A surface feature shape in which a surface has a dimple, a depression or indentation on a surface.
A multi-tissue plant structure (PO:0025496) that develops in response to a biotic stress (PSO:0000004).
A texture quality in which a surface is covered or partially by with facets.
A texture quality in which a surface has the appearance and/or consistency of moss, especially those species in Polytrichaceae (Bryophyta).
A texture quality in which a surface has the consistency and thickness of a paper bag (thin and dry).
A quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being covered in short, dense, fine hairs, which give the appearance of felt.
A coating quality in which a surface is covered in a whitish, powdery film or dust.
A shedability quality in which a part can readily be detached from its location but it normally (in nature) stays attached; detachable.
A structural quality inhering in an object by virtue of the object's susceptibility to breaks, without significant deformation (strain) when subjected to stress.
A plant gall that is part of a leaf and which appears as a portion of swollen tissue, similar to a blister.
A plant gall that is located on a bud.
A plant gall that is monothalamous and solid, with a shape reminiscent of a bullet. Gall is usually subspherical or subelliptical in shape.
A plant gall that has a detached larval chamber capable of rolling around a hollow chamber located inside the gall.
A plant gall that is located on a bud and which consists of layers of scale leaves or similar phyllomes that surround the inducer's chamber.
A portion of plant tissue that is fed upon by a gall inhabitant.
A cavity that is occupied by one or more gall inhabitants.
